statement.p:
Let E be an oriented solid region in space, and let
\Omega=H\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz.
With the standard orientation,
\boxed{\int_E\Omega=\iiint_E H\,dV.}
If E is described by a smooth coordinate map T:D\to E, then
\boxed{\int_E\Omega=\iiint_D T^*\Omega.}

Let E be the solid cylinder x^2+y^2\le4,\qquad 0\le z\le3, with the standard orientation. Let \Omega=(1+z)\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz. Use cylindrical coordinates: x=r\cos\theta,\qquad y=r\sin\theta,\qquad z=z. From , dx\wedge dy\wedge dz=r\,dr\wedge d\theta\wedge dz. So T^*\Omega=(1+z)r\,dr\wedge d\theta\wedge dz. Therefore
\int_E\Omega \amp= \int_0^2\int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^3(1+z)r\,dz\,d\theta\,dr \amp= \left(\int_0^2 r\,dr\right)\left(\int_0^{2\pi}d\theta\right)\left(\int_0^3(1+z)\,dz\right) \amp= 2\cdot2\pi\cdot\frac{15}{2} \amp= 30\pi.
So \boxed{\int_E (1+z)\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz=30\pi.}

subsection.p:
For curves,
\boxed{\int_{-C}\omega=-\int_C\omega.}
Here -C means the same curve with the opposite direction.

For surfaces,
\boxed{\int_{-S}\Phi=-\int_S\Phi.}
Here -S means the same surface with the opposite choice of normal side.
